{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582997"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:03:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:03:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1697"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1697"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.14,0,0.01,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59279"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1697"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44690"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1012"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3437"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59279"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old Indigenous man presents to General Practice five months after a mechanical aortic valve replacement for severe aortic stenosis. He reports new flu-like symptoms, fever, and generalised joint aches. On auscultation of the chest you note a diastolic murmur with ejection click in addition to bibasal coarse crackles. There is clinical evidence of anaemia. Two consecutive blood cultures are positive for Staphylococcus aureus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Infective endocarditis","Acute rheumatic fever","Viral myocarditis","Pneumonia leading to sepsis","Septic arthritis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient fulfils two major and two minor of Duke\u2019s (modified) criteria confirming a diagnosis of\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Einfective endocarditis.\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0The diastolic murmur alludes to a new murmur such as aortic regurgitation secondary to endocarditis, with bibasal coarse crepitations suggesting consequent left ventricular failure. An ejection click is to be expected with a mechanical aortic valve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArtificial heart valves significantly increase the risk of infective endocarditis, with risk heightened in the first six months following valve replacement and later after high risk procedures such as dental or respiratory tract surgery. Staphylococcus aureus is the most common pathogen in infective endocarditis. Streptococcus viridans, the secondmost common, is classically implicated in subacute infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHigh output states such as sepsis or anaemia\u00a0may lead to a systolic flow murmur due to turbulent blood flow. However, the features of left ventricular failure (pulmonary oedema) and pathogen involved make this patient\u2019s sepsis less likely to be from an extracardiac source. Both \u003Cstrong\u003Epneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eseptic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E are unable to explain all of the patient\u2019s presenting features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute rheumatic fever\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune reaction following a Group A Streptococcus infection, disproportionally affecting Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander patients. Where there is no known past history of acute rheumatic fever, evidence of a preceding Group A streptococcus infection (i.e. pharyngitis) should be present for diagnosis. Whilst flu-like symptoms and fever are the typical presentation of\u003Cstrong\u003E viral myocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E, the two positive blood cultures make this unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Streptococcus viridans is a common pathogen in subacute infective endocarditis","Infective endocarditis is diagnosed using the modified Duke\u2019s criteria","A new heart murmur in the setting of febrile illness should raise high suspicion for infective endocarditis","Major diagnostic criteria for infective endocarditis include two separate blood cultures for typical pathogens, evidence of endocardial involvement in echocardiography, and a new valvular regurgitation"],"references":["Topan A, Carstina D, Slavcovici A, Rancea R, Capalneanu R, Lupse M. Assesment of the Duke criteria for the diagnosis of infective endocarditis after twenty-years. An analysis of 241 cases. Clujul Med. 2015;88(3):321-326. doi:10.15386/cjmed-469","Ben-Dov I, Berry E. Acute rheumatic fever in adults over the age of 45 years: an analysis of 23 patients together with a review of the literature. Semin Arthritis Rheum. 1980 Nov;10(2):100-10. doi: 10.1016/0049-0172(80)90003-7. PMID: 7292018."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44690"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1697"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44690"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-06T13:49:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-06T13:49:28+10:30"},"